column4: <content>The attribution of the Deluge in Peter [sic] Bruegel the Elder is in my view not convincing. The picture does not fit into any period of his career. A certain relation to the engraved so-called Small Landscape series is no support for an attribution to P. Bruegel, as this series is certainly not by Bruegel. [...][scan]</content>

<parts.title>[Tekening FG in potlood].[recto] 'The Deluge', Panel, 9 3/4 x 17 3/4 inches, ex. Masing Coll. Vienna. Certificates by Friedländer (A'dam 15-2-54) & Valentiner (Los Angeles Jan. 16, 55): Pieter Bruegel the Elder; [toegevoegde vermelding]: 'F.G. Not P.B.I, does not fit, into any of his periods. A certain relation to the engraved small landscapes series does not prove Bruegel's authorship; [verso] as these are not by Bruegel. Above all the vedute character speaks against P.B. It is a work derived from him, the landscape silhouette or the horizon to be compared with Winterlandscape with Bird Trap. The stressing of the white speak against P. Bruegel. The trees are coarse when in my view correspond with his. It is the work of a close follower of Bruegel. The fine painting of the ducks so different from P.B. birds, might possibly indicate Jan Brueghel the Younger, but cf. also Jacob Grimmer, Village Street, fully signed and dated 1583 (or 1589) De Boer Exh. 1934, N° 128 (pl. 18). Photograph shown by Hallsborough 17-7-57.[scan]</parts.title>
<documentation.title>Helsche en de Fluweelen Brueghel en hun invloed op de kunst in de Nederlanden : naar aanleiding van de tentoonstelling in de kunsthandel P. De Boer</documentation.title>
